{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:09:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604238"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:50:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:50:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15810"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.16,0.65,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8501"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90540"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"651"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman admitted to hospital with an exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease is reviewed due to serum potassium of 3.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0). She has a medical history of hypertension, heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications are amlodipine, spironolactone, and paracetamol. Since admission, she has received regular nebulised salbutamol, regular nebulised ipratropium, oral prednisolone, and as-needed paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on 2 L/min oxygen via nasal cannulae, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her chest has scattered end-expiratory wheeze with good air entry bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely contributing to the hypokalaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prednisolone","Ipratropium","Spironolactone","Salbutamol","Amlodipine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has developed mild hypokalaemia during admission for an exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Among the medications listed, \u003Cstrong\u003Esalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause. Beta-2 agonists cause an intracellular shift of potassium through stimulation of the sodium-potassium ATPase pump. This effect is particularly notable with frequent or high-dose nebulised therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to hypokalaemia through mineralocorticoid effects, but this usually occurs with prolonged therapy rather than short-term use for an acute exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is a potassium-sparing diuretic that typically causes potassium retention, not loss. In fact, it is commonly used in heart failure patients to prevent hypokalaemia that can occur with other diuretics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, does not typically affect potassium levels. While some antihypertensives (particularly loop and thiazide diuretics) can cause hypokalaemia, calcium channel blockers do not have this effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpratropium\u003C/strong\u003E is an anticholinergic bronchodilator that works by blocking muscarinic receptors. It does not have direct effects on potassium homeostasis and is not associated with electrolyte disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of this mild hypokalaemia would involve oral potassium supplementation if needed, and consideration of reducing the frequency of nebulised salbutamol if clinically appropriate. Regular monitoring of potassium levels is important during bronchodilator therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Common medications that can cause hypokalaemia include beta-2 agonists, insulin, and diuretics.","Salbutamol causes intracellular shift of potassium through beta-2 receptor stimulation.","Spironolactone typically causes potassium retention, not loss."],"references":["Castro D, Sharma S. Hypokalemia. [Updated 2024 Mar 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482465/","Veltri KT, Mason C. Medication-induced hypokalemia. Pharmacy and Therapeutics. 2015 Mar;40(3):185. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4357351/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90540"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90540"},"attributes":{"createdAt":